{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17598884","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17598884"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":1,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T11:45:41+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T11:45:41+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15513"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"15513","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/15513"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.05,0.44,0.05,0.15,0.32]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"8204"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"69882"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"8204","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/8204"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15513"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"55338"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"9"},{"type":"tags","id":"14"},{"type":"tags","id":"24"},{"type":"tags","id":"35"},{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"1094"},{"type":"tags","id":"1254"},{"type":"tags","id":"1722"},{"type":"tags","id":"2551"},{"type":"tags","id":"4927"},{"type":"tags","id":"4950"},{"type":"tags","id":"6770"},{"type":"tags","id":"11129"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"19851"},{"type":"contributions","id":"19856"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"69882","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/69882"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA five-year-old child presents to the Emergency Department with sudden onset sore throat and difficulty breathing. The child is sitting upright and leaning forward, drooling, and appears distressed. The parent reports the symptoms started two hours ago.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is most characteristic of acute epiglottitis?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Productive cough with purulent sputum","Absence of cough","Symptoms developing over 48-72 hours","Caused by Streptococcus pyogenes","Preference for supine positioning"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EAcute epiglottitis is characterised by the \u003Cstrong\u003Eabsence of cough\u003C/strong\u003E, which helps distinguish it from other upper respiratory tract infections. The classic presentation includes rapid onset of symptoms (rather than \u003Cstrong\u003Esymptoms developing over 48-72 hours\u003C/strong\u003E), with the patient typically adopting the \u0027tripod position\u0027 - sitting upright and leaning forward (not showing a \u003Cstrong\u003Epreference for supine positioning\u003C/strong\u003E) to maximise airway patency.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EWhile \u003Cstrong\u003EStreptococcus pyogenes\u003C/strong\u003E can cause throat infections, acute epiglottitis is typically caused by Haemophilus influenzae type b (Hib), though this has become less common since the introduction of Hib vaccination. A \u003Cstrong\u003Eproductive cough with purulent sputum\u003C/strong\u003E is more characteristic of bronchitis or pneumonia rather than epiglottitis.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe combination of sudden onset sore throat, drooling, and respiratory distress without cough should raise immediate concern for epiglottitis, which is a medical emergency requiring urgent airway management.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["Acute epiglottitis is typically caused by Haemophilus influenzae type b (Hib), though incidence has decreased with vaccination","The absence of cough is a key distinguishing feature of epiglottitis","The classic \u0027tripod position\u0027 (sitting upright, leaning forward) is characteristic of epiglottitis"],"references":["Wick F, Ballmer PE, Haller A. Acute epiglottis in adults. Swiss Med Wkly. 2002 Oct 12;132(37-38):541-7. doi: 10.4414/smw.2002.10050. PMID: 12557859.","Sutton AE, Guerra AM, Waseem M. Epiglottitis. [Updated 2024 Oct 5]. In: StatPearls [Internet]. Treasure Island (FL): StatPearls Publishing; 2024 Jan-. Available from: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK430960/","Mason, R. J., Broaddus, V. C., Martin, T. R., King, T. E., Schraufnagel, D., Murray, J. F., \u0026 Nadel, J. A. (2010). Murray and Nadel\u0027s textbook of respiratory medicine E-book: 2-volume set. Elsevier Health Sciences.","Kumar, V., Abbas, A. K., \u0026 Aster, J. C. (Eds.). (2012). Robbins basic pathology e-book. Elsevier Health Science"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"55338"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15513"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"55338","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/55338"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-12-12T21:44:21+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-12-12T21:46:14+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"8204"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"69882"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"9","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/9"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc76","name":"Paediatrics","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-01-16T08:39:03+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"14","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/14"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udda0","name":"Infectious Diseases","synonyms":["ID"],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2021-05-21T07:51:58+09:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{